Abstract = {Classical Chinese translation presents significant challenges: manual
   methods suffer from high costs and inconsistent quality, while both
   traditional machine translation and approaches relying solely on Large
   Language Models often fail to adequately capture intricate semantic
   nuances and cultural specificities. To overcome these limitations, this
   study proposes an LLM-driven multi-agent framework that decomposes
   translation into word-level interpretation, paragraph-level generation,
   and multi-dimensional review, integrating a specialized Key Word
   Interpretation Database, Retrieval-Augmented Generation, and iterative
   feedback. Experiments on The Records of the Grand Historian of China:
   The Hereditary Houses and the Biographies, Volume 7-10 show average
   improvements of 18.8-25.7\% in BLEURT, BLEU-1, and METEOR over
   single-model baselines, with
